			<h2>Weak Verbs I</h2>
			<p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">C</span>lass <span aria-label="one">I</span>
				weak verbs have an <abbr
					title="The base form of a verb. In Modern English: to [verb]">infinitive</abbr>
				ending in
				<strong>-an</strong> or <strong>-rian</strong>. For example, <em>fremman - to do</em>, <em>nerian -
					to save</em>, <em>hieran - to hear</em>, <em>feran -
					to go</em>, <em>sendan - to send</em>, <em>l&aelig;ran - to teach</em>. When conjugated, the
				third-person
				present singular ends in <strong>-þ</strong> or <strong>-eþ</strong>,
				and present plural ends in <strong>-aþ</strong>.</p>
			<p>Examine the form of the verb in the first sentence <em>'the king goes to the mountain'</em> vs the
				second: <em>'the kings go to the mountain'</em>:</p>
