			<p>
				Since Modern English verbs do not conjugate as heavily, it can be difficult for speakers get used to the
				variety of suffixes in Old English. However, due to the flexibility of word order in Old English, often the
				conjugation of the verb is the only way to tell what subject the verb is linked to, as the subject
				may come after the verb, or may even not be present. For example, in the sample below, the subject
				only appears in the first part of the sentence: <em>I heard the Lord and went to him</em>.
			</p>
