			<p>
				You will notice that while all Class I weak verbs are similar and have the same endings, there are
				some minor variations in the letter before the stem. How a word changes depends on whether there is
				a <abbr title="A long vowel is a vowel whose pronunciation is the same as its letter name">long
					vowel</abbr> or a <abbr
					title="A short vowel sound is what you hear in words like 'bat' or 'gem'">short
					vowel</abbr>, and whether or not there
				is a double consonant. As a result, Class I verbs are traditionally divided into two subclasses.
			</p>
			<p>Subclass A are verbs like <em>fremman</em> and <em>nerian</em>:</p>
			<ol>
				<li><em>Fremman</em> has a short vowel followed by two consonants</li>
				<li><em>Nerian</em> has a short vowel followed by an 'ri'</li>
			</ol>
			<p>Subclass B are verbs are like <em>hieran</em>:</p>
			<ol>
				<li><em>Hieran</em> has a long vowel followed by a single consonant.</li>
			</ol>
